 costs, while abnormal losses are reported separately as conventional costs.\"", "\"TARGET COSTING SEQUENCE\":\"This quiz involves matching the stages required to describe the sequence used when operating target costing. Target costing starts with ascertaining the selling price that the market would accept and then works backward to determine the target production cost.\"", "\"ENVIRONMENTAL COST OF PRODUCTION RUN\":\"This quiz involves calculating the environmental cost of a production run using input/output analysis. The company manufactures a product using two chemicals, and any waste produced must be disposed of at a cost.\"", "\"RELEVANT COST OF MATERIAL X\":\"This quiz involves calculating the relevant cost per unit of material X for the manufacture of a special version of a product. The relevant cost is determined by comparing the opportunity cost of selling the material versus using it as a substitute for another material.\"", "\"DEFINITION OF OPPORTUNITY COST\":\"This quiz defines opportunity cost as 'The value of a benefit sacrificed in favour of an alternative course of action' and asks which term is best described by this definition.\"", "\"TOTAL RELEVANT COST OF LABOUR FOR THE CONTRACT\":\"This quiz involves calculating the total relevant cost of labour for a contract that requires 600 labour hours to complete. The calculation considers spare labour capacity, weekend overtime, and the opportunity cost of diverting labour from another product.\"", "\"SUNK COST OF THE PROJECT\":\"This quiz involves identifying the sunk cost of a project, which is a cost that has been incurred and cannot be recovered. The question provides details of the costs incurred to date and additional expenditures required.\"", "\"RELEVANT COST OF USING THE MACHINE\":\"This quiz involves calculating the total relevant cost of using a machine on a short-term contract, considering loss of sale proceeds, running costs, and dismantling and removal costs.\"", "\"RELEVANT CASH FLOW\":\"This quiz involves identifying the best description of the term 'relevant cash flow,' which refers to the difference in future operating cash flows resulting from a decision.\"", "\"RELEVANT COST OF MATERIALS\":\"This quiz involves calculating the total relevant cost of materials for a project, considering the current purchase price and resale price of materials in inventory.\"", "\"SHORT-TERM DECISIONS\":\"This quiz involves determining the truth of statements about short-term decisions, specifically regarding joint costs and differential costs between internal and external services.\"", "\"RELEVANT COST OF MATERIAL B FOR SPECIAL ORDER\":\"This quiz involves calculating the total relevant cost of material B for a special order, considering the cost of quantity to be bought and the opportunity cost of quantity in hand.\"", "\"COMPONENTS TO BUY IN\":\"This quiz involves determining the cost-effectiveness of buying in components versus producing them in-house, considering material, labor, and variable overhead costs.\"", "\"SUNK COST\":\"Sunk costs are costs that have already been incurred and cannot be recovered. They are not relevant to future decision-making. For example, the $1.20 per metre for the cable is a sunk cost.\"", "\"RELEVANT COST OF MATERIAL Z\":\"The total relevant cost of material Z is calculated by comparing three options: buying Z now and storing it, buying Z in one month\u2019s time, or converting material Y. The lowest cost option is chosen.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}